1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:03,897
On November 7, 1940, the Tacoma Narrows Bridge

2
00:00:04,017 --> 00:00:05,520
collapsed into Puget Sound.

3
00:00:06,341 --> 00:00:07,763
It had opened on July 1.

4
00:00:08,525 --> 00:00:10,508
Four months later, it was gone.

5
00:00:11,830 --> 00:00:13,713
The wind that morning was not extraordinary.

6
00:00:14,574 --> 00:00:15,556
It was measured at 38 miles per hour

7
00:00:15,576 --> 00:00:20,043
at 7:30 a.m. and about 42 miles per

8
00:00:20,043 --> 00:00:23,268
hour near the bridge's east end two hours

9
00:00:23,348 --> 00:00:26,644
later. The bridge had already ridden through earlier

10
00:00:26,764 --> 00:00:30,231
autumn storms with winds over 50 miles per

11
00:00:30,271 --> 00:00:33,638
hour. What it could not survive was the

12
00:00:33,678 --> 00:00:35,922
way its own motion changed the air around

13
00:00:36,003 --> 00:00:38,548
it, and what that air then did back

14
00:00:38,608 --> 00:00:40,816
to the bridge. For a little over an

15
00:00:40,856 --> 00:00:43,561
hour before the collapse, the bridge twisted.

16
00:00:43,621 --> 00:00:47,206
Not simply swayed, and not only bounced.

17
00:00:48,028 --> 00:00:50,612
The roadway rotated along its length,

18
00:00:50,632 --> 00:00:52,415
one side rising as the other fell,

19
00:00:52,455 --> 00:00:54,859
in a motion that grew steadily larger.

20
00:00:56,141 --> 00:00:58,885
Leonard Coatsworth, whose car had been thrown against

21
00:00:58,925 --> 00:01:01,529
the curb, climbed out and crawled toward the

22
00:01:01,649 --> 00:01:05,155
East Tower as the deck rolled beneath him.

23
00:01:05,155 --> 00:01:07,158
Engineers and photographers were watching.

24
00:01:07,158 --> 00:01:11,864
Motion-picture footage survives. The bridge did not

25
00:01:11,944 --> 00:01:15,069
fail because November 7 brought some unprecedented

26
00:01:15,129 --> 00:01:17,792
gale. It failed because the bridge and the

27
00:01:17,853 --> 00:01:20,716
wind entered a feedback cycle the design had

28
00:01:20,777 --> 00:01:21,998
never been tested against.

29
00:01:22,839 --> 00:01:24,081
Once that cycle took hold,

30
00:01:24,742 --> 00:01:27,666
each oscillation helped feed the next.

31
00:01:27,666 --> 00:01:30,131
This episode is not about a freak storm

32
00:01:30,171 --> 00:01:33,116
or a cartoon version of bad engineering.

33
00:01:33,958 --> 00:01:35,661
It is about what happens when a structure

34
00:01:35,721 --> 00:01:37,845
is optimized for the forces engineers know how

35
00:01:37,865 --> 00:01:40,691
to calculate, while a different class of forces

36
00:01:40,731 --> 00:01:43,596
remains outside the design process.

37
00:01:44,521 --> 00:01:46,683
The original proposal for a bridge across the

38
00:01:46,723 --> 00:01:48,925
Narrows came from Clark Eldridge,

39
00:01:49,366 --> 00:01:51,468
lead engineer for the Washington State Highway

40
00:01:51,508 --> 00:01:54,491
Department. His design was conservative by the

41
00:01:54,531 --> 00:01:57,714
standards of the day: a two-lane suspension bridge

42
00:01:57,794 --> 00:02:00,076
with deep, open stiffening trusses,

43
00:02:00,096 --> 00:02:03,820
twenty-five feet deep, along the deck.

44
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:05,721
That design was not the one that got

45
00:02:05,782 --> 00:02:09,005
built. When Washington sought federal funding,

46
00:02:09,645 --> 00:02:12,568
the Public Works Administration required outside

47
00:02:12,668 --> 00:02:17,256
consultants. Leon Moisseiff, one of the most prominent

48
00:02:17,336 --> 00:02:19,680
suspension bridge engineers in the United States,

49
00:02:20,461 --> 00:02:24,167
redesigned the superstructure. He had helped shape the

50
00:02:24,227 --> 00:02:26,871
theory behind some of the country's great suspension

51
00:02:26,911 --> 00:02:29,876
bridges. He was respected and accomplished.

52
00:02:30,757 --> 00:02:33,321
He also told the PWA his revisions would

53
00:02:33,382 --> 00:02:35,805
cut the estimated cost from roughly eleven million

54
00:02:35,805 --> 00:02:38,890
dollars to seven. The critical change was the

55
00:02:38,930 --> 00:02:42,837
deck. Instead of Eldridge's deep open trusses,

56
00:02:43,558 --> 00:02:46,883
Moisseiff used solid plate girders just eight feet

57
00:02:46,963 --> 00:02:49,968
deep. Where Eldridge's deck would have let much

58
00:02:50,048 --> 00:02:53,473
more air pass through, Moisseiff's presented a broader

59
00:02:53,514 --> 00:02:55,016
solid surface to the wind.

60
00:02:55,957 --> 00:02:58,161
The bridge was also extraordinarily slender.

61
00:02:59,102 --> 00:03:03,229
Its center span was 2,800 feet long,

62
00:03:03,229 --> 00:03:05,412
while the deck was only 39 feet wide

63
00:03:05,492 --> 00:03:09,038
between the cables, a ratio of one to

64
00:03:09,058 --> 00:03:11,822
seventy-two. For bridge designers of the 1930s,

65
00:03:12,904 --> 00:03:15,027
that kind of lightness and grace looked like

66
00:03:15,067 --> 00:03:17,871
the future. The redesign was approved.

67
00:03:19,053 --> 00:03:21,076
Construction began in November 1938.

68
00:03:21,136 --> 00:03:24,180
The bridge opened to traffic on July 1,

69
00:03:24,241 --> 00:03:28,866
1940. Almost immediately, it moved.

70
00:03:29,909 --> 00:03:32,214
Drivers and pedestrians noticed the vertical

71
00:03:32,314 --> 00:03:35,481
undulation first. The deck rose and fell in

72
00:03:35,521 --> 00:03:39,289
long waves. The motion was so conspicuous that

73
00:03:39,309 --> 00:03:41,234
the bridge quickly acquired a nickname:

74
00:03:41,915 --> 00:03:46,345
Galloping Gertie. Engineers knew about the movement.

75
00:03:46,345 --> 00:03:49,089
Before the collapse, the state had already hired

76
00:03:49,129 --> 00:03:51,753
University of Washington engineer F.

77
00:03:52,374 --> 00:03:56,920
B. Farquharson to study the oscillations and recommend

78
00:03:56,960 --> 00:04:00,325
remedies. Tie-down cables had been installed on the

79
00:04:00,385 --> 00:04:03,690
side spans. Wind deflectors were under active

80
00:04:03,770 --> 00:04:07,238
consideration. The movement was not treated as an

81
00:04:07,318 --> 00:04:10,723
immediate emergency. It was treated as an alarming

82
00:04:10,803 --> 00:04:13,607
peculiarity, but still a manageable one.

83
00:04:14,608 --> 00:04:17,052
People drove across the bridge for the experience.

84
00:04:18,114 --> 00:04:20,657
Each day the bridge moved and remained standing

85
00:04:21,278 --> 00:04:23,401
made the motion easier to categorize as a

86
00:04:23,481 --> 00:04:26,165
property of the bridge rather than evidence of

87
00:04:26,185 --> 00:04:27,868
a failure already in progress.

88
00:04:28,969 --> 00:04:32,671
That matters. Visible anomaly had been normalized

89
00:04:32,932 --> 00:04:35,715
before the catastrophic mode ever arrived.

90
00:04:37,257 --> 00:04:38,658
On the morning of November 7,

91
00:04:39,119 --> 00:04:40,481
the bridge's behavior changed.

92
00:04:41,201 --> 00:04:43,584
The familiar vertical motion gave way to torsional

93
00:04:43,624 --> 00:04:46,488
motion. Shortly after 10:00 a.m.,

94
00:04:47,068 --> 00:04:48,250
the deck began twisting.

95
00:04:48,870 --> 00:04:53,676
By 11:10 a.m., the center span had fallen.

96
00:04:54,382 --> 00:04:57,467
What followed was not the wind simply overpowering

97
00:04:57,507 --> 00:05:01,033
the structure. It was a flexible structure interacting

98
00:05:01,073 --> 00:05:03,577
with wind in a way the design framework

99
00:05:03,617 --> 00:05:04,959
of the time did not know how to

100
00:05:05,039 --> 00:05:07,763
evaluate well. To understand why,

101
00:05:07,783 --> 00:05:10,107
you have to look at five conditions that

102
00:05:10,127 --> 00:05:12,050
were in place before the first cable was

103
00:05:12,090 --> 00:05:17,018
spun. First: the redesign prioritized slenderness,

104
00:05:17,759 --> 00:05:20,203
economy, and visual grace.

105
00:05:21,010 --> 00:05:23,733
Moisseiff's work grew out of deflection theory,

106
00:05:24,473 --> 00:05:26,855
an advanced framework for suspension bridges.

107
00:05:27,736 --> 00:05:29,818
In that framework, the dead weight of the

108
00:05:29,878 --> 00:05:33,141
bridge, the cable system, and the stiffness already

109
00:05:33,201 --> 00:05:35,504
built into the structure could do far more

110
00:05:35,744 --> 00:05:38,386
of the stabilizing work than older practice had

111
00:05:38,426 --> 00:05:40,588
assumed. The payoff was real.

112
00:05:41,269 --> 00:05:43,231
Bridges could be longer, lighter,

113
00:05:43,871 --> 00:05:46,574
cheaper, and in the eyes of many engineers,

114
00:05:47,295 --> 00:05:50,480
more beautiful. For the loads that theory modeled

115
00:05:50,560 --> 00:05:52,444
well, it was powerful.

116
00:05:53,466 --> 00:05:56,352
Tacoma Narrows was not built by ignoring engineering.

117
00:05:57,053 --> 00:05:59,418
It was built by applying advanced engineering within

118
00:05:59,458 --> 00:06:01,723
the limits of what that engineering had formalized.

119
00:06:02,765 --> 00:06:07,033
Second: bridge design theory still treated wind mainly

120
00:06:07,134 --> 00:06:10,079
as a static load, not a dynamic conversation

121
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:11,322
between air and structure.

122
00:06:12,324 --> 00:06:16,432
In the 1930s, suspension bridge engineers were highly

123
00:06:16,512 --> 00:06:18,617
capable at analyzing gravity loads,

124
00:06:19,098 --> 00:06:22,725
traffic loads, and steady horizontal wind pressure.

125
00:06:22,725 --> 00:06:24,248
What they did not yet have was a

126
00:06:24,348 --> 00:06:27,515
mature, standardized framework for aerodynamic

127
00:06:27,575 --> 00:06:30,421
behavior in very flexible long-span bridges.

128
00:06:31,322 --> 00:06:33,527
Wind was generally treated as a force that

129
00:06:33,607 --> 00:06:36,032
pushed on the structure, not as something that

130
00:06:36,112 --> 00:06:39,058
changed when the structure itself began to move.

131
00:06:39,980 --> 00:06:42,064
That distinction is everything.

132
00:06:42,064 --> 00:06:43,406
If a bridge moves in wind,

133
00:06:43,907 --> 00:06:45,789
it changes the airflow around its deck.

134
00:06:46,571 --> 00:06:48,754
The changed airflow alters the force on the

135
00:06:48,794 --> 00:06:52,079
deck. That altered force changes the next motion.

136
00:06:53,160 --> 00:06:55,604
The bridge is no longer just resisting wind.

137
00:06:56,405 --> 00:06:58,247
It is helping create the conditions of its

138
00:06:58,428 --> 00:07:01,953
own next displacement. Dynamic wind-tunnel testing

139
00:07:02,353 --> 00:07:04,997
existed in aeronautics. It was not yet a

140
00:07:05,057 --> 00:07:08,322
routine requirement in suspension-bridge design.

141
00:07:08,875 --> 00:07:12,800
Third: the bridge's motion had already been absorbed

142
00:07:12,880 --> 00:07:14,362
into the category of spectacle.

143
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:16,885
Between July and November 1940,

144
00:07:16,985 --> 00:07:19,648
the bridge's oscillations were visible,

145
00:07:20,289 --> 00:07:22,652
documented, and widely discussed.

146
00:07:23,473 --> 00:07:24,955
Farquharson was studying them.

147
00:07:25,856 --> 00:07:27,198
Remedies were being developed.

148
00:07:28,099 --> 00:07:31,463
But traffic continued, the nickname stuck,

149
00:07:31,483 --> 00:07:33,445
and the bridge's motion became part of its

150
00:07:33,545 --> 00:07:35,608
identity in public life.

151
00:07:36,010 --> 00:07:38,993
When a system produces conspicuous abnormal behavior

152
00:07:39,234 --> 00:07:42,537
and survives, people begin to discount the warning.

153
00:07:43,458 --> 00:07:45,661
The bridge taught its observers that movement could

154
00:07:45,701 --> 00:07:47,703
be dramatic without being fatal.

155
00:07:48,444 --> 00:07:50,687
That lesson held until it didn't.

156
00:07:51,948 --> 00:07:54,711
Fourth: the design had not been subjected to

157
00:07:54,751 --> 00:07:57,715
the kind of aerodynamic testing that later became

158
00:07:57,795 --> 00:08:00,678
standard. This was the clearest gap.

159
00:08:01,759 --> 00:08:03,802
The problem was not that the calculations were

160
00:08:03,882 --> 00:08:07,261
sloppy. The problem was that the design process

161
00:08:07,321 --> 00:08:10,344
of 1940 did not yet routinely demand a

162
00:08:10,405 --> 00:08:14,309
dynamic aerodynamic investigation of a bridge deck

163
00:08:14,389 --> 00:08:16,852
like this one. After the collapse,

164
00:08:17,612 --> 00:08:20,075
the federal investigating board identified excessive

165
00:08:20,115 --> 00:08:23,299
flexibility, the aerodynamic effect of the solid

166
00:08:23,299 --> 00:08:26,602
plate-girder deck, and the need for wind-tunnel model

167
00:08:26,662 --> 00:08:28,024
testing as central lessons.

168
00:08:29,005 --> 00:08:31,668
Those lessons were learned after the bridge fell,

169
00:08:32,429 --> 00:08:33,810
not before it was built.

170
00:08:34,516 --> 00:08:38,544
Fifth: once the bridge entered large torsional motion,

171
00:08:39,206 --> 00:08:41,671
the motion itself began feeding the forces acting

172
00:08:41,771 --> 00:08:45,238
on it. Engineers still debate some details of

173
00:08:45,279 --> 00:08:47,363
the transition from vertical oscillation to

174
00:08:47,423 --> 00:08:50,935
catastrophic twisting. But the standard modern

175
00:08:50,996 --> 00:08:53,919
explanation centers on self-excited torsional flutter,

176
00:08:54,620 --> 00:08:57,023
a self-reinforcing twisting instability.

177
00:08:58,004 --> 00:08:59,326
In that kind of instability,

178
00:08:59,806 --> 00:09:02,650
the twisting of the deck changes the airflow

179
00:09:02,710 --> 00:09:04,512
in a way that adds energy back into

180
00:09:04,552 --> 00:09:07,856
the twist. The motion becomes self-reinforcing.

181
00:09:08,577 --> 00:09:10,179
The wind did not need to become a

182
00:09:10,239 --> 00:09:12,842
hurricane. It only needed to keep supplying the

183
00:09:12,902 --> 00:09:14,965
flow field that the moving bridge was already

184
00:09:15,025 --> 00:09:18,291
turning into fuel. This is why Tacoma Narrows

185
00:09:18,772 --> 00:09:20,195
is so often misunderstood.

186
00:09:21,137 --> 00:09:23,302
The famous footage tempts people to call it

187
00:09:23,362 --> 00:09:26,108
a simple resonance story, as if the wind

188
00:09:26,148 --> 00:09:29,255
just happened to hit one magic frequency and

189
00:09:29,275 --> 00:09:31,460
the bridge obediently shook itself apart.

190
00:09:32,562 --> 00:09:34,206
That is too simple.

191
00:09:34,206 --> 00:09:37,233
The stronger account is an aerodynamic one:

192
00:09:38,316 --> 00:09:42,606
vertical motion, vortex effects, torsional

193
00:09:42,786 --> 00:09:46,495
instability, and a bridge deck so flexible that

194
00:09:46,595 --> 00:09:48,299
once the twisting mode took hold,

195
00:09:49,021 --> 00:09:51,366
the airflow and the structure began driving each

196
00:09:51,466 --> 00:09:54,460
other. The bridge did not merely fail in

197
00:09:54,500 --> 00:09:57,905
the wind. It became aerodynamically unstable in the

198
00:09:57,945 --> 00:10:00,869
wind. The collapse had an immediate effect on

199
00:10:00,909 --> 00:10:03,973
the profession, even if the exact mechanism was

200
00:10:04,053 --> 00:10:06,036
not settled in a single afternoon.

201
00:10:07,378 --> 00:10:08,960
Investigations began at once.

202
00:10:09,821 --> 00:10:13,086
The federal board reported in March 1941.

203
00:10:13,842 --> 00:10:16,588
University of Washington wind-tunnel work continued

204
00:10:16,629 --> 00:10:19,756
through the 1940s. The Advisory Board on the

205
00:10:19,816 --> 00:10:22,482
Investigation of Suspension Bridges met from 1942 to

206
00:10:22,502 --> 00:10:28,271
1954. Engineers re-evaluated other long-span

207
00:10:28,311 --> 00:10:31,715
suspension bridges and began designing later spans

208
00:10:32,015 --> 00:10:34,498
with far greater attention to aerodynamic stability.

209
00:10:35,519 --> 00:10:37,501
The replacement Tacoma Narrows Bridge,

210
00:10:38,162 --> 00:10:41,626
opened in 1950, looked much more like Eldridge's

211
00:10:41,726 --> 00:10:44,909
original instinct than Moisseiff's 1940 deck.

212
00:10:45,730 --> 00:10:49,114
It used a much deeper open stiffening truss,

213
00:10:49,114 --> 00:10:51,416
features to let air pass through the deck,

214
00:10:52,037 --> 00:10:53,618
and additional damping devices.

215
00:10:54,379 --> 00:10:56,501
That was not an aesthetic correction.

216
00:10:57,462 --> 00:10:59,404
It was a new engineering answer to a

217
00:10:59,464 --> 00:11:02,907
newly formalized problem. The collapse did not reveal

218
00:11:03,008 --> 00:11:05,910
engineering negligence in the simple moralized sense.

219
00:11:06,851 --> 00:11:08,153
Moisseiff was not guessing.

220
00:11:09,154 --> 00:11:11,496
He was applying the best accepted theory available

221
00:11:11,556 --> 00:11:14,279
to him, and that theory had worked impressively

222
00:11:14,339 --> 00:11:17,971
within its domain. What the collapse revealed was

223
00:11:18,011 --> 00:11:20,174
that the domain itself had an edge.

224
00:11:21,075 --> 00:11:23,578
Past that edge, the equations were not wrong.

225
00:11:24,079 --> 00:11:26,883
They were incomplete. The deeper failure was not

226
00:11:26,903 --> 00:11:28,144
that the bridge was slender,

227
00:11:28,705 --> 00:11:30,888
or beautiful, or inexpensive.

228
00:11:32,109 --> 00:11:33,932
It was that the design tools used to

229
00:11:33,992 --> 00:11:36,655
judge the bridge were optimized for loads they

230
00:11:36,695 --> 00:11:37,817
had been built to handle,

231
00:11:38,558 --> 00:11:41,502
while aerodynamic instability in flexible bridge decks

232
00:11:42,082 --> 00:11:44,425
had not yet been fully absorbed into ordinary

233
00:11:44,505 --> 00:11:47,993
bridge practice. The bridge was not dynamically vetted

234
00:11:48,053 --> 00:11:51,097
against that problem in the way later generations

235
00:11:51,158 --> 00:11:54,663
would consider essential. This kind of failure recurs

236
00:11:54,763 --> 00:11:56,265
across the history of engineering.

237
00:11:57,207 --> 00:11:59,490
It is not the failure of knowingly ignoring

238
00:11:59,570 --> 00:12:02,235
a risk. It is the failure of working

239
00:12:02,275 --> 00:12:05,019
inside a framework that has not yet formalized

240
00:12:05,099 --> 00:12:07,563
a real risk, even when clues to that

241
00:12:07,603 --> 00:12:09,385
risk are already present.

242
00:12:10,447 --> 00:12:14,974
In aviation, aerodynamic behavior was already central.

243
00:12:14,974 --> 00:12:18,422
In suspension-bridge design, it had not yet crossed

244
00:12:18,523 --> 00:12:20,467
fully into routine design practice.

245
00:12:21,249 --> 00:12:22,392
The knowledge was nearby.

246
00:12:22,412 --> 00:12:25,259
The discipline boundary was real.

247
00:12:26,482 --> 00:12:30,150
After November 7, 1940, that boundary did not

248
00:12:30,210 --> 00:12:33,636
survive intact. The field changed because it had

249
00:12:33,676 --> 00:12:36,940
to. Wind-tunnel testing became commonplace.

250
00:12:37,701 --> 00:12:40,303
Aerodynamic stability became a standard concern in

251
00:12:40,303 --> 00:12:43,907
long-span bridge design. Designers paid much closer

252
00:12:43,967 --> 00:12:46,871
attention to deck shape, torsional stiffness,

253
00:12:47,511 --> 00:12:50,615
damping, and the way moving structures feed energy

254
00:12:50,695 --> 00:12:51,856
back into the air around them.

255
00:12:52,837 --> 00:12:54,299
That is how engineering learns.

256
00:12:55,080 --> 00:12:58,123
Not cleanly. Not abstractly.

257
00:12:58,123 --> 00:13:00,426
Often by discovering, in the wreckage of a

258
00:13:00,486 --> 00:13:03,491
real structure, the exact point where a trusted

259
00:13:03,551 --> 00:13:05,173
model stopped matching the world.

260
00:13:06,655 --> 00:13:08,879
The Tacoma Narrows Bridge twisted for a little

261
00:13:08,939 --> 00:13:10,241
over an hour before it fell.

262
00:13:11,242 --> 00:13:13,986
Cameras were running. Engineers were watching.

263
00:13:15,148 --> 00:13:17,812
By then, the bridge was already doing something

264
00:13:17,872 --> 00:13:20,215
its designers had never been required to prove

265
00:13:20,275 --> 00:13:23,568
it could survive. Everything needed for the failure

266
00:13:23,628 --> 00:13:25,952
was present long before November 7:

267
00:13:26,773 --> 00:13:29,377
the shallow plate-girder deck, the extraordinary

268
00:13:29,457 --> 00:13:32,381
slenderness, the weak torsional resistance,

269
00:13:32,982 --> 00:13:35,306
the absence of dynamic aerodynamic testing,

270
00:13:35,987 --> 00:13:37,589
and a profession that had not yet made

271
00:13:37,629 --> 00:13:40,874
those questions routine. The wind that morning did

272
00:13:40,914 --> 00:13:42,376
not create the design weakness.

273
00:13:43,037 --> 00:13:46,002
It revealed it. What failed at Tacoma Narrows

274
00:13:46,082 --> 00:13:48,726
was a bridge. What else failed was the

275
00:13:48,786 --> 00:13:50,368
boundary of a model.

276
00:13:50,652 --> 00:13:51,818
The failure was real.

277
00:13:52,542 --> 00:13:53,788
The cause chain was longer.

278
00:13:54,632 --> 00:13:57,105
Next time: another design failure.

279
00:13:57,125 --> 00:14:01,024
Another system that taught itself to ignore what

280
00:14:01,085 --> 00:14:02,931
it had not yet learned how to name.
